Document: Physics Interpolation Introduction
Path: godot/tutorials/physics/interpolation/physics_interpolation_introduction.rst
Summary: This document introduces the concept of physics interpolation in Godot Engine, explaining its purpose and how it differs from simple extrapolation.

Physics interpolation is a technique used to smooth out the visual representation of physics objects in games, especially when the physics simulation runs at a different rate than the rendering frame rate. This is particularly important for achieving smooth motion and preventing jittery or jerky movements.

The core idea behind physics interpolation is to render the game world at a point in time that is slightly behind the current physics simulation time. When the game renders a frame, it doesn't just display the physics state from the exact moment the frame started. Instead, it interpolates between the physics states of two previous simulation steps to determine the visual position and rotation of objects.

This approach contrasts with extrapolation, where the system predicts future states based on current velocity. Extrapolation can lead to inaccuracies if the prediction is wrong, causing visual artifacts. Interpolation, by using past states, guarantees that the rendered position is a valid state that the physics engine has already processed or will process.

In Godot Engine, physics interpolation is handled automatically when enabled. The physics engine runs at a fixed timestep (e.g., 60 times per second), while the rendering can run at a variable frame rate. Interpolation ensures that the visual representation aligns smoothly with the physics simulation, regardless of the rendering frame rate.

Key Rule: Physics interpolation renders the game world at a point in time between two previous physics simulation steps, ensuring smooth visual motion.

The benefits of using physics interpolation include:
*   **Smoother Visuals:** Eliminates jitter and stuttering, especially on lower-end hardware or when physics calculations are demanding.
*   **Consistent Experience:** Provides a more stable and predictable visual experience for the player.
*   **Reduced Artifacts:** Avoids the visual errors that can occur with extrapolation.

To enable physics interpolation in Godot, you typically need to configure project settings related to physics and rendering. The engine then manages the interpolation process behind the scenes.
---CHUNK---
Document: Physics Interpolation Introduction
Path: godot/tutorials/physics/interpolation/physics_interpolation_introduction.rst
Summary: This document introduces the concept of physics interpolation in Godot Engine.

Introduction

Physics interpolation is a technique used to smooth out the visual representation of physics objects in games. When physics simulations run at a fixed timestep (e.g., 60 times per second), and rendering occurs at a variable rate (e.g., 30 to 120 frames per second), visual discrepancies can arise. This can lead to jerky or stuttering motion, especially when the rendering framerate drops below the physics timestep.

Physics interpolation addresses this by rendering frames *between* the physics steps. Instead of rendering at the exact moment of a physics step, the game renders at an intermediate point between two physics steps. This allows the visual position of objects to be smoothly interpolated from their previous physics state to their current physics state, resulting in a much smoother visual experience for the player, regardless of the rendering framerate.

In Godot Engine, physics interpolation is handled automatically when using the `PhysicsServer` or when using nodes that rely on the physics engine, such as `RigidBody3D` or `CharacterBody3D`. The engine calculates the interpolated positions and applies them during the rendering process.

This tutorial will explore how physics interpolation works in Godot and how to leverage it to create smoother-looking physics simulations in your games.
---CHUNK---
Document: Physics Interpolation Introduction
Path: godot/tutorials/physics/interpolation/physics_interpolation_introduction.rst
Summary: Explains the difference between fixed physics ticks and variable rendered frames and the resulting visual issues.

Physics ticks and rendered frames
One key concept to understand in Godot is the distinction between physics ticks (sometimes referred to as iterations or physics frames), and rendered frames. The physics proceeds at a fixed tick rate (set in Project Settings > Physics > Common > Physics Tick per Second), which defaults to 60 ticks per second.

However, the engine does not necessarily render at the same rate. Although many monitors refresh at 60 Hz (cycles per second), many refresh at completely different frequencies (e.g. 75 Hz, 144 Hz, 240 Hz or more). Even though a monitor may be able to show a new frame e.g. 60 times a second, there is no guarantee that the CPU and GPU will be able to supply frames at this rate. For instance, when running with V-Sync, the computer may be too slow for 60 and only reach the deadlines for 30 FPS, in which case the frames you see will change at 30 FPS (resulting in stuttering).

But there is a problem here. What happens if the physics ticks do not coincide with frames? What happens if the physics tick rate is out of phase with the frame rate? Or worse, what happens if the physics tick rate is lower than the rendered frame rate?

This problem is easier to understand if we consider an extreme scenario. If you set the physics tick rate to 10 ticks per second, in a simple game with a rendered frame rate of 60 FPS. If we plot a graph of the positions of an object against the rendered frames, you can see that the positions will appear to "jump" every 1/10th of a second, rather than giving a smooth motion. When the physics calculates a new position for a new object, it is not rendered in this position for just one frame, but for 6 frames.

This jump can be seen in other combinations of tick / frame rate as glitches, or jitter, caused by this staircasing effect due to the discrepancy between physics tick time and rendered frame time.
